  "prompt": "Does Belarus have expectation of privacy in public space (or not, like Russia and United States)?",
  "response": "In Belarus, as in many other countries, the expectation of privacy in public spaces is generally limited. Under Belarusian law, individuals typically do not have a strong expectation of privacy when they are in public areas where they can be observed by others. This is similar to the situation in countries like Russia and the United States, where activities conducted in public spaces may be subject to surveillance or public observation without expectation of privacy.\n\nHowever, the specifics of privacy laws can vary based on context and interpretations of the law. In Belarus, like in many nations, there are also laws that protect individuals from certain types of invasive surveillance and data collection, but these laws can be influenced by the political climate and governmental oversight. It\u2019s important to consult legal experts or specific legal texts for detailed insights into privacy rights in Belarus, especially given the country's unique political situation.",
